{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512618"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:57:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:57:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11923"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11923"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.03,0.31,0.57,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43905"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4520"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11923"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28884"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1773"},{"type":"tags","id":"2182"},{"type":"tags","id":"4919"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6668"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6675"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42685"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43905"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man reports to his General Practitioner with coarsening of his facial features over several years. In addition, he reports low libido and decreased energy. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On physical examination frontal bossing (Image) and enlarged hands are noted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["24-hour urinary-free cortisol","ACTH assay","Growth hormone level","Serum IGF-1 level","Serum prolactin level"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFrom the patient\u0027s symptoms and his facial appearance, the most likely diagnosis is acromegaly. His features might also be considered cushingoid, but enlargement of his hands would be more in keeping with acromegaly. The underlying problem will most likely be a functional pituitary adenoma or hyperplasia. Such lesions can present with acromegaly, as in this patient, prolactinomas and Cushing\u2019s syndrome. Because \u003Cstrong\u003Egrowth hormone\u003C/strong\u003E is secreted in a highly pulsatile fashion, obtaining random serum levels is not reliable. \u003Cstrong\u003EIGF-1 \u003C/strong\u003Eis measured to screen for growth hormone excess. Serum \u003Cstrong\u003Eprolactin\u003C/strong\u003E level is useful to screen for prolactinomas; \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urinary free cortisol \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003EACTH assay\u003C/strong\u003E are useful screens for Cushing\u2019s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["IGF-1 is measured to screen for growth hormone excess."],"references":["Banskota S, Adamson DC. Pituitary Adenomas: From Diagnosis to Therapeutics. Biomedicines. 2021;30;9(5):494. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33946142/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28884"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11923"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16250"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16250"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https